<p> 24 March is World TB Day, commemorating the time in 1882 when Dr Robert Koch first announced his discovery of <i>Mycobacterium tuberculosis</i>, the bacillus that causes tuberculosis. </p> <p> About one third of the world's population is estimated to be infected with TB. Infected people have a lifetime risk of falling ill with TB of 10%, but mortality has declined sharply in recent decades. </p> <p> Since March 2014, when we created our first <i>Scrip</i> infographic on the topic, a second new drug has been approved for multi-drug resistant TB &ndash; Otsuka's Deltyba (delanamid) &ndash; following that of Johnson &amp; Johnson's Sirturo (bedaquiline), which was the first novel TB medicine approved in 40 years. </p> <p> To recognize World TB Day and provide an update on the landscape, including the funding situation and R&amp;D activities, <i>Scrip</i> brings you our new TB Infographic. </p> <p> <a target="_blank" href="http://marketing.scripintelligence.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/11/2015/03/TB-Day_SCRIP1503_low-res.pdf"><img src="-/media/627BC18554FD45849753CBAAED89CA64.ashx"> </a> </p> <p> See also our <a target="_new" href="http://www.scripintelligence.com/home/5-questions-for-Janssen-Indias-boss-on-TB-research-and-Sirturo-357435">interview with Janssen India managing director Sanjiv Navangul on Sirturo and TB research</a> </p> <p> and <a target="_new" href="http://www.scripintelligence.com/policyregulation/World-TB-Day-2015-new-drugs-new-methods-new-guidance-357444">World TB Day 2015: new drugs, new methods, new guidance</a> </p> 
